We have photographed elopements in a lot of locations over the years, narrowed down our travel schedule to work in our very favorites, and there is only one âman madeâ place on the list we base our schedule around. Amangiri is a remote luxury resort tucked deep in the white sandstone mesas in southern Utah. Everything about it was designed with the unique desert property in mind, and the details are so thoughtful I often struggle to find the line between epic landscape and beautiful architecture. Weâve become friends with the staff, familiar with the place, and fallen in love with the creativity behind planning and photographing elopements here.
-
So when Mary & Richard reached out to us, we couldnât say yes fast enough. They trusted us with their timeline and plans, and I am so stoked on what we came up with. Mary grew up in Wyoming and most of her favorite memories include the mountains, and they wanted their elopement to be stress-free and flow perfectly into a relaxing honeymoon, so naturally @amangiri was perfect for them. When Mary sent me photos of her fairytale dress with a stunning full-length slit, I knew we had to incorporate horseback riding! This was our first time shooting with horses and it was so much fun! From their peaceful ceremony, gorgeous candlelit dinner, cozy sunrise from their room, and then literally riding off into the desert together at the end, their elopement was so much fun and one we wonât soon forget. I canât wait to share more from this incredible day ð

Thanks to you three boys for making the trip so dang unforgettable and to @alannapotter for the best book/podcast list :)

Sunset from the best spot with the worst name.ð´ Since Arches is closed we came to Dead Horse Point multiple nights. No matter the weather, last light here was always magic. Photo by @travisburkephotography

The desert is asleep at 4 am. Except for us, of course. My footfalls are even, my breathing erratic as the uphills. We run to keep the night creatures away. The real ones and the imagined ones too. We stop at the star gate on the edge of an inky black abyss. Here I am, a small creature admiring the delicate intersection between storm and starry silence.
-

Happy Earth day from one of the most richly imaginative landscapes on earth. Let's practice #leavenotrace tactics and follow legal rules, yes. But more than that, I think it's important to establish your own set of outdoor ethics. Because I find I adhere to those in my heart as well as in my mind. Cheers beautiful humans - to all the ways we can be more mindful of the weight of our collective footsteps.ð @keen #keenambassador #earthday #protectwhereweplay pc: @travisburkephotography

Right now my job requires that I fly a lot and I get questions about how I reconcile that increased carbon footprint as someone who cherishes our environment. As more of us fall in love with traveling one fairly straightforward way that Iâd like to share on here is the idea of carbon offsetting. There are quite a few services (I use one called Terrapass) where you can calculate your CO2 footprint from transportation, electricity, etc and pay to offset that amount through funding things like tree planting and alternative energy projects. I think a few airlines allow you to directly purchase credits against each flight, but Iâve found it easier to just do it for the entire year. Not a perfect system, but thought it might be something you guys are interested in. Or maybe you know more/better ones that I can implement into my life :) update: you guys mentioned two other ones @mossy.earth and @treeeraco
-
